# Fluff Date: 2026-02-26 19:50:04
overview:<p>The Sidewinder is a 75-ton Clan OmniMech produced by Clan Cloud Cobra, entering production during the Late Succession Wars era as a heavy fire-support platform intended to complement the Cloud Cobras' touman in preparation for the anticipated invasion of the Inner Sphere. The design shares the distinctive leg structure of the Timber Wolf, a similarity so pronounced that the two designs are difficult to distinguish at range. This visual resemblance, combined with Clan Cloud Cobra's exclusion from the invading Clans, has made the Sidewinder one of the most elusive and least-documented OmniMechs in existence, a 'Mech known more by reputation than by confirmed battlefield reports.</p>

capabilities:<p>Built on a Krait Mark VI Endo Steel frame and powered by a 300-rated XL fusion engine, the Sidewinder achieves a top speed of 64.8 kilometers per hour, notably slower than the Timber Wolf it visually resembles. Cloud Cobra engineers compensated for this reduced straight-line velocity by integrating both jump jets and a MASC system into the base chassis, granting pilots burst speed capability up to 86.4 kilometers per hour and the ability to navigate rough terrain that would stall heavier assault platforms. This combination of burst mobility and jump capability makes the Sidewinder a difficult target to pin down despite its lower cruising speed.</p><p>Twelve tons of Takeda Industries ferro-fibrous armor provide protection comparable to other heavy Clan OmniMechs, offering solid survivability without excessive weight expenditure. The design's primary asset is its generous 34.75 tons of pod space, giving commanders substantial flexibility in mission configuration. In its Prime configuration, the Sidewinder carries a Gauss rifle as its primary striking weapon, supported by paired LRM-10 launchers fitted with Artemis IV fire control systems for accurate long-range indirect fire. A large pulse laser and two medium pulse lasers provide layered close-range firepower, while an anti-missile system offers defensive screening against incoming salvos. Twelve double heat sinks manage the thermal load efficiently, though the Gauss rifle's minimal heat generation means the design runs cool even under sustained fire.</p>

deployment:<p>The Sidewinder Prime is the only documented configuration of the design, reflecting the extreme scarcity of intelligence on the chassis as a whole. Cloud Cobra garrison formations and Trial forces represent the primary operators, though the confirmed sighting of a Jade Falcon machine on Baker 3 in 3053 suggests that at least some Sidewinders have changed hands through Trials of Possession. How many additional Sidewinders may have been present along invasion corridors, misidentified as Timber Wolves in the confusion of combat, remains a persistent question among Inner Sphere intelligence analysts. The Prime configuration's emphasis on long-range precision firepower makes it well suited to the Cloud Cobras' doctrinal preference for disciplined, methodical engagements over close-range brawling.</p>

history:<p>The Sidewinder was developed at Complex H-1 on Homer during the Late Succession Wars period, giving Cloud Cobra warriors access to a heavy OmniMech platform distinct from the ubiquitous Timber Wolf that dominated Clan toumans. The Cloud Cobras invested heavily in the Sidewinder as part of their preparations for the anticipated invasion of the Inner Sphere, viewing the design as a vehicle for demonstrating their worthiness to participate in the great crusade against the Successor States.</p><p>When it became apparent that the Cloud Cobras would not be selected among the invading Clans, the Sidewinder's strategic purpose shifted from invasion spearhead to Homeworld garrison and Trial asset. The design's visual similarity to the Timber Wolf proved both advantageous and problematic. While the resemblance complicated Inner Sphere intelligence efforts to catalog Clan designs, it also meant the Sidewinder rarely received individual recognition in battlefield reports, even on the rare occasions it was encountered. The only confirmed Inner Sphere sighting, a holopic from Baker 3 in 3053, depicted what was identified as a Clan Jade Falcon machine, suggesting that at least some Sidewinders changed hands through Trials of Possession or battlefield salvage during the invasion era.</p><p>Complex H-1 on Homer maintained continuous Sidewinder production under Cloud Cobra ownership from the Late Succession Wars through the early Dark Age era. The Wars of Reaving and subsequent upheavals in the Clan Homeworlds left the facility's later ownership uncertain, with records from the late Dark Age onward listing the factory under ambiguous Clan control. Despite this uncertainty surrounding its later provenance, the Sidewinder's production history spanning centuries speaks to a design that served its originating Clan reliably, even if it never achieved the fame or widespread deployment of more prominent Clan OmniMechs.</p>

